1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,000
We're ready, John.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:13,000
We're rolling.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:19,000
I'm Emilye Crosby of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:27,000
And I'm conducting this oral history as part of the Civil Rights History Project, which is sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution's African American,

6
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:34,000
or sorry, National Museum of African American History and Culture and the American Folklife Center of the Library of Congress.

7
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Today is August 24th, 2013, and we're in the Northborough, Massachusetts Free Library, and I'm here with Mrs. Virginia Sims, George, her husband, Frederick George, and John Bishop, whose videotaping.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,000
I'm doing the videography.

9
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Thank you for joining us.

10
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:03,000
I was wondering if you could tell me about your family and where you're from and growing up.

11
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:17,000
I'm actually from Virginia, and when I say that everybody, you know, quickly say, oh, you're named after the state, but my grandmother was named Virginia, and my father indicated I was named after my grandmother.

12
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,000
Who probably was named after the state?

13
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:43,000
But I was one in Newport News, Virginia, which is on a tidewater, and I have one brother, who's 13 months older than I am, and my father and mother separated when I was a very young child, and so I was raised by my father, my brother and I, for the most part.

14
00:01:43,000 --> 00:02:05,000
So I went to school in Newport News, I'll just share when I was coming up, Newport News was very mistakenly.

15
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:34,000
And I grew up, and I just in town, and my father remarried, and after he remarried, he, they bought a home, and we moved out to the suburbs, and when we moved to the suburbs, what was happening was all the white people were leaving that area and going further out, where they would not be living with blacks.

16
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:50,000
There were two people, I think, still there, when we moved, and she was on next door neighbor, and she happened to say to my father that had I known, you know, that you guys were such good people, I never would have sold my home.

17
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:11,000
But that was my first, it really experienced with the idea that there was a difference. And then going up to visit my aunt, who still lived on the street where I was born and grew up, I actually took a bus, which was the first time I'd ever ridden a bus in town.

18
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:40,000
And I was probably about 12, I didn't know really the etiquette of the bus that I got on, and there's a seat, you know, like this way and then the rest of the seats go, and I sat there, and there was a white lady next to me, and I wasn't sure, I didn't know, I shouldn't have sat next to her, she jumped up, she moved to the other side, and she started to look at me, scrambling and frowning, and I felt so bad, and I remember going home, talking to my father,

19
00:03:40,000 --> 00:04:02,000
and that's when my father talked to me a little bit about rage and the experiences, and in his mind, the thing to make a difference was education. And my father would always say, you know, you need to get your education, because if you get it up here, no one can take it from you.

20
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:19,000
That was one of the first things, and my brother had lived in Germany for about five years, and he came home, and he and my father went to a hardware store, and a white clerk came up and said, what can I do for you boys?

21
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:34,000
And I think my brother having lived in Germany for such a long period of time, you know, realized that really wasn't white, and I remember him telling us that, he said, you know, this is my father, he's no boy, and he left.

22
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:44,000
But in Virginia, where I grew, they used the words boys and girls as a means of demeaning like people.

23
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:55,000
So I had decided that I wanted to be a lawyer, and I was going to, you know, fight for the civil rights of all African-American people.

24
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:07,000
I graduated from high school, and we didn't have counselors, you know, that really gave the kind of advice that our children get today.

25
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:21,000
So I ended up going to Virginia Union University, and actually my father had gone there for a year, and I think the dorm that I stayed in used to be a man's dorm, and it really had turned into a woman's dorm.

26
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,000
So I went there with not really thinking I was going to be a lawyer, and majoring in history.

27
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:33,000
And it was straight history, because the intent was to go to law school somewhere somehow.

28
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:36,000
So that's a little bit about me.

29
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Can I ask if you follow? Sure. Questions? So what kind of work did your father do?

30
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,000
I followed with the postman.

31
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:56,000
And so you said that when you, when he remarried and bought the house and moved out to the more suburban area, so was this in the 50s?

32
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:04,000
Yes, yes, yes. And that's when, and this is when there's that sort of transition with white smooth out.

33
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Right, and moving out and blacks moving out to their area.

34
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:14,000
So the neighbor lived there long enough to get a sense of your family, but had already sold her house.

35
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:21,000
Had already sold her house, and it was too late to turn around, you know, but she was saying, if I'd known, I wouldn't have.

36
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
That's a really kind of thing.

37
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Yeah, that she would, nothing, it would be true, but just that she would have that thought and articulated in that area.

38
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Never will forget that, you know, because the neighborhood that we moved in was, as I said, was transitioning.

39
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:47,000
There were a couple of doctors, African American doctors, business people and everything like that.

40
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:53,000
All, you know, to the white people, it was like they're black. You know, we can't mingle, can't live together.

41
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
And so they sold their homes and they left.

42
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Really considered the class issues at all.

43
00:06:58,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Or, yeah.

44
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Or that we were people.

45
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Right.

46
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:16,000
You know, and that probably nice people as we turned out, you know, to be, but, you know, my father was a postman, he was very active in organizations and very much encouraged us to go.

47
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
And get educated.

48
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:22,000
So at this point in Virginia, well, let me actually back up.

49
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:27,000
So do you remember things like the Brown decision or the little rock integration or anything?

50
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Yeah, yeah.

51
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:43,000
So it all on TV, you know, and it was interesting and something that just, you know, never thought about, you know, because so our schools were black.

52
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:50,000
We had our neighborhoods, RIP Black. When I was a little kid, there was a store.

53
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:59,000
I remember Jefferson Avenue was a busy street. And on that store, there was a department store run by white people.

54
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
And that's where we would go and we would shop.

55
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,000
But we had our own, you know, like restaurants or places to go.

56
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:18,000
It was totally separated. So you didn't really come in contact with white people of my father being a postman worked on a route that was white.

57
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:21,000
And so, and he enjoyed it.

58
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:29,000
He'd come home Christmas with these big bags of presents because all the, you know, post all the people really loved and respected him.

59
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
And they remembered him at Christmas.

60
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:38,000
But, yeah, it was done that time, you know, we expected to go to a black school.

61
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:48,000
We had black teachers. We had no white teachers, you know. And everybody, the principal, the counselors, the teachers, everything was ever with black.

62
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:55,000
It's interesting, too, because Virginia at that time probably must have been while you were in school because of the timing.

63
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:15,000
You know, it was closing schools. The Prince Edward County Schools, I think, that were part of the Brown decision that when they were forced to integrate, you know, Virginia was the one with the states leading the way in closing black schools rather than, or closing public schools rather than integrate.

64
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
Now that only happened in a couple of communities.

65
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:29,000
That's what I was going to say. So, in our community, at the time, it was still, you know, so I was born in Newport News next stresses Hampton + Hampton + Warwick, and then you had Hampton + Warwick.

66
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:39,000
What started to happen was that Newport News, and it probably had something to do with voting and representation and everything like that.

67
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:52,000
They began to expand Newport News over to one work. So that probably was taken into consideration that a lot of white people had moved out of the town and they were in war.

68
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:59,000
And so then the boundaries were moved so that you could keep it, but, you know, it was a way of life for us.

69
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
So in Newport News, we're African Americans able to register and vote at that time.

70
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:04,000
Yeah, they were. We were.

71
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:12,000
Okay. So in some ways, it's a, you know, I know different states have different cultures and different parts of the state.

72
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:28,000
So the thing to also remember is Newport News had first-of-the-month shipyard/sailor influx ship building. So they had this Amongus business because they built these very, but three city blocks long ships and everything.

73
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:39,000
So you had, you know, that industry there plus you had Air Force, Army, Navy, merchant Marines, you name it.

74
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
First of the month, everybody these ships, these sailors and everybody would hit the town.

75
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
So needless to say, I didn't go out.

76
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Okay.

77
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:52,000
I had to be, I had to be Shaffer Road.

78
00:10:52,000 --> 00:11:04,000
And the worst Shaffer Road of all was my brother, you know, I couldn't go, I couldn't go out unless I went with my brother or with my neighbor and friend because her mother would take us to places and bring us back.

79
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,000
But so you had that happening in town at the same time.

80
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:12,000
I was going to say so there's in some ways there's this federal influence probably.

81
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:18,000
And there's a strong enough African American community to have a self-contained business.

82
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Right. Right. And in our churches of course were like everything.

83
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:35,000
Fuehnerhomes, churches, drugstores because one of my first jobs or not my first but one of the jobs I had was I worked as a soda-jerk clerk in a drugstore.

84
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:46,000
And the person, one of the owners of the drugstore, son was my brother's best friend and lived in the block just ahead of us plus another doctor.

85
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:50,000
So Dr. Jones and Dr. Tucker owned the drugstore.

86
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:51,000
Okay.

87
00:11:51,000 --> 00:12:02,000
And so of course all of us, blacks came to the same place again our prescriptions to have Sundays or by the things that we need it that they carried.

88
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:09,000
So it sounds like it must have been in many ways a good community to grow up in.

89
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:25,000
I think so. You know, I think you know sometimes I share a threat. I was a debitant and all like that because we had our own society and being a debitant meant that you didn't date or you had not dated and everything like that.

90
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:28,000
And you were selected to be presented.

91
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:39,000
I know it's foreign to people today but because I wasn't able to go out and to date I could not date until I was 16.

92
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:54,000
And when I was 16 I was presented to society where you had meetings, you had practice and everything and it was a debitant criterion where you wore white dress, gloves, pearls, Pearl Earrings, etc.

93
00:12:54,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And you danced with your father.

94
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:58,000
Did you enjoy that?

95
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:04,000
I loved it. I remember actually my stepmother made my dress and it was so big.

96
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:17,000
My uncle, my dad wasn't driving at that time and so my uncle had a big, oh, Cadillac and I remember sitting in the back seat and my dress took the whole seat, you know, and everything like that.

97
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:26,000
So it was fun, you know. I think of it, you know, I did. I really feel that I had a lot of great experiences.

98
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:34,000
I had a lot of great people who influenced me and helped me.

99
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:45,000
One of my very best friends, I babysat for her. Her name was Mary and Benz and her husband was a first black urologist in Virginia.

100
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:59,000
And I used to babysat for her and she was also encouraging me to go to school and helped to get my wardrobe and helped me to save and everything like that and the same for the next door neighbor.

101
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
So I felt that I had a lot of support.

102
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,000
Wonderful. Are you okay?

103
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Okay. You mentioned that incident on the bus and deciding that you wanted to be a lawyer where those connected. I mean, was it?

104
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:26,000
You know, I don't know. I just remember that incident had a real impact on me because, you know, I just got on the bus.

105
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:39,000
I hadn't done anything to her. I didn't even know who she was. Probably would never see her again, but it began to help me to understand that there was a difference in me because I was black and she was white.

106
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:45,000
And that's when you began to know that they're differences.

107
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:54,000
And I remember my father would come home and tell me about some of his people he cared male to.

108
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:08,000
Their daughters were getting married, you know, going to high school, getting married. And that was the thing that they did and he did not want me to do who that he wanted me to go to school because he wanted me to be better.

109
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:14,000
I wanted me to be better in my life, having an opportunity, I guess, to be better in my life.

110
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:26,000
So I couldn't say, I guess the other thing, there was a lawyer. Her name was Marion L. Poe. And she was the first African American female lawyer that I ever knew.

111
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:34,000
Or so. And I just thought she was marvelous and wonderful. And I wanted to be like a like attorney, Poe.

112
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:36,000
How did you see me? How did you know that church?

113
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:46,000
She was a church. And I just knew her from church. I went to school with her grandkids, probably.

114
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:57,000
Did you remember whether you and other children in the community or at church, whether there were discussions of the NAACP or the events like the Montgomery Pust Boy Codd or things like that?

115
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:00,000
No, I can't remember.

116
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Yeah. And so when did what year did you start college?

117
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,000
1959.

118
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:11,000
1959. So you were there in fall 1959?

119
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:15,000
The fall 1959 was my first semester. What was that like?

120
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:19,000
There was a lot of fun. It was my first time away from home.

121
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:27,000
Yeah. And living on my own. And I remember I got in a little trouble because in Virginia,

122
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:32,000
it was a very, it was a Baptist school. And you just couldn't do things.

123
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:40,000
I remember when you wanted to go out, you were supposed to ask. And I remember and you swore to go with another student and everything.

124
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:45,000
And I remember going downtown to Richmond by myself without checking out without asking.

125
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:52,000
And I met Marie Sallason, who was one of the people who was arrested.

126
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
She's, you've seen her, may have seen her picture.

127
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:04,000
Marie Sallason and Patricia Washington, well the two of them were roommates and they were diagonally across the hall.

128
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:11,000
And we said they used to get in trouble and I would maybe ground it because of them, but we hung together and we had a lot of fun.

129
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:21,000
You know, doing crazy things like I remember one time Marie Sann, Patricia Washington were chasing each other around the dorm or something and the dorm matron

130
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:25,000
making too much noise and came in and grounded us.

131
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:28,000
Because I was sitting on a bed laughing.

132
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Well, they were being bad and I was part of it because I was supporting them.

133
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:40,000
And they were supposed to be clean in the room because we were going away for one of the holidays or something.

134
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And then they weren't getting it done and all like that.

135
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:52,000
But I really enjoyed the first year because the dorm had a basement and you could go down in the basement.

136
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:54,000
They'd have dances.

137
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:58,000
So even though if we were grounded, we sneak down there anyway.

138
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:01,000
You know, like take a, because it was the washed area as well.

139
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:07,000
So we take a blouse or something like we were going to wash clothes and go in a dance and then come back.

140
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
So we turned the clock back.

141
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
So that when we went, we ran before curfew.

142
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
So these are things Fred doesn't know of how we did.

143
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:30,000
We did a little devilish thing and I never told my father but I remember asking my father if I could go to the Penn Relays and he said yes.

144
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:33,000
And I didn't tell him how it was going and he didn't ask.

145
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,000
So we actually went in a car.

146
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:41,000
My reads Patricia Washington and I just went with some guy to Philadelphia to the Penn Relays.

147
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:48,000
Well Patricia Washington was from there, from outside of Philadelphia in a place called North Town.

148
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:55,000
And so we were all going to stay at Patricia Washington's house and we had an opportunity to meet her parents.

149
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:00,000
And it was really nice for a relationship as a matter of fact.

150
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:09,000
I think the next year I went to Philadelphia and I stayed with Patricia Washington and I worked during this summer before going back to school.

151
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:15,000
So when you all would go off, sneak off to the downtown Richmond without signing out.

152
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:20,000
Is that because you're going to do something that you couldn't sign out for just resisting those regulations?

153
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:27,000
Probably a little bit of both but one time we went down there so I have to tell you Patricia Washington could pass with white.

154
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:37,000
And None of us could understand — her parents looked white and her mother and father they really looked white and Patricia Washington looked white.

155
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:45,000
So we went to Richmond and I don't remember when this was, we went to Richmond and (Marie + Pat + Virginia in Richmond) Pat went into a white barbershop, a white barbershop.

156
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:48,000
We waited outside, she went in and got her hair cut.

157
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:51,000
And they didn't know she was black because she looked white.

158
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:55,000
She was doing that just because of the segregation and things like that.

159
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:57,000
We thought it was funny.

160
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:00,000
So we went with her and waited and she got her hair cut.

161
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:03,000
We came out and said oh they don't know.

162
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:06,000
Instead of means of resistance.

163
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:17,000
And Marie so Marie's Patricia Washington and I, we hung together and we did things together and consequently when they were talking about the sit-ins of three of us,

164
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:24,000
we didn't know band it together of course and we were going and all three of us got arrested.

165
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:29,000
Do you remember how you felt when you first heard or do you remember how you first heard about the sit-ins?

166
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:31,000
Well they were going all around.

167
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:39,000
I mean you had, I think it was in North Carolina with the Woolworth that you had heard about them.

168
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:46,000
And then people were actually coming to the campuses talking about getting involved.

169
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,000
Really Martin Luther King had come.

170
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:56,000
We had two people who were ministers, Frank Pinkston and Charles Sherrod.

171
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
I remember Shirley Miller Sherrod.

172
00:20:58,000 --> 00:20:59,000
You remember her?

173
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,000
Okay.

174
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:06,000
But Charles, the two Charles and Frank sort of led, pulled us together.

175
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:15,000
And we started to talk about it, we had meetings, we started to talk about it and strategized what we would do in Richmond.

176
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
Can you describe Charles Sherrod and Frank Pinkston?

177
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,000
Oh it's been so long ago.

178
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:36,000
I remember Frank, I remember board glasses, he was a minister and it's very nice.

179
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:43,000
Both of them are very nice, very articulate and great leaders.

180
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:44,000
Great leaders.

181
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:47,000
So they were really the kind of driving force?

182
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:54,000
They were the driving force and they were the ones that helped us to understand that they probably would be taken.

183
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:02,000
Because it was obvious that they were our leaders and that one go down, the other one was standout.

184
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:07,000
So it wasn't a matter of us falling apart because the two of them had been arrested.

185
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:09,000
So they prepared you for what would happen?

186
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:10,000
They prepared us for what happened.

187
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:19,000
We had other people that were working with us and everything and they talked to us about the need for nonviolence, the need to become,

188
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:29,000
the need not to let people get to us because certainly there would be that happening to us.

189
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:33,000
And so and it did.

190
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,000
Were you afraid?

191
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:37,000
I was, I wasn't afraid.

192
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:43,000
I was so excited and I was so proud and the interesting thing is I never talked about it.

193
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:56,000
I mean, I don't even know when I finally told Fred, I might have told him Irlon and our relationship but I remember my young nephew coming and he was telling all his friends that Jenny had been arrested and all.

194
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:01,000
But I never, never ever talked about it.

195
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:11,000
It was just something that I had done because I felt it needed to be done because I just felt that black people were treated so unfairly.

196
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:15,000
So I was excited, you know, I was excited when I was shocked.

197
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:24,000
It was after I got out of jail and everything and that's a different story but I came home and I was looking at the night news and I saw myself.

198
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:27,000
I saw them lead me out of the store.

199
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:40,000
I remember them putting me in a Paddy (wagon), in a squad car to the, I guess, to the paddy wagon came and then beat me from there and put me into a paddy wagon and I said, oh my god, I better call my father.

200
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,000
He may see the news, okay.

201
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:48,000
And that's when I realized, you know, I had, I needed to connect.

202
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:51,000
Yeah. So it seemed more serious when you actually saw that.

203
00:23:51,000 --> 00:24:01,000
It was real. It happened and it was documented that it had happened and I needed to let my dad know.

204
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:04,000
Yeah. I'm comfortable. Is it okay?

205
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:06,000
It's always wonderful.

206
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:12,000
Can you, were you arrested on the first sit and you participated in or did you participate?

207
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:14,000
That was their one or two before that?

208
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:15,000
It was one.

209
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:16,000
We walked, we marched.

210
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:17,000
Okay.

211
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:25,000
And we marched downtown and then we went back and we went to this department store called Thalhimers.

212
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:32,000
Thalhimers is very much like Macy's with our Macy's, you know.

213
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:39,000
And the interesting thing about that store was we could shop there, but that was it.

214
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:42,000
We could go there, we could spend our money.

215
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:47,000
If we wanted something to eat, we had to go to the basement and they had a stand.

216
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:50,000
No, it was orange, Julia stands where you could go.

217
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:52,000
That's what we had to do.

218
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:58,000
And we spent as much money as anyone else with wood and did spend.

219
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:04,000
But there was the Richmond, the Richmond, I always call it the Richmond, where we were not allowed.

220
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:07,000
Black folks couldn't go in there.

221
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:10,000
And so that was our target.

222
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:12,000
And so is that something you'd experienced?

223
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:15,000
I mean you'd been down there and used that store before?

224
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:18,000
Oh yeah, I've been to the store. I've been down to the counter.

225
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:22,000
The orange juice, the hot dog, the soda or something like that.

226
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:27,000
And then you asked the question, well, how money is in our money good?

227
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:32,000
You know, our money spends, we purchase, we support the store.

228
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:38,000
And yet we can't, you know, enjoy the Richmond room because of our color.

229
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:44,000
You know, and that's when we just said, you know, that's when those of us, you know, we thought about it today.

230
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:46,000
That can't be, not today.

231
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:47,000
We need to change.

232
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:49,000
Times need to change.

233
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,000
Were there students that tried to talk you out of it?

234
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:54,000
No, not at all.

235
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:59,000
The students, the faculty, nobody said anything, derogatory.

236
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:02,000
We just got a lot of support.

237
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:07,000
Did you, I know this was true of students at some schools, but did you worry about being put out of school?

238
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:09,000
No, not at all.

239
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:10,000
Yeah.

240
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,000
We had support, we had full support.

241
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:15,000
Can you describe the support?

242
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:23,000
Well, there was never, I never remember anyone talking to us about what we were talking about.

243
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:28,000
It was about what we did that it was wrong or that we shouldn't have done it.

244
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,000
We didn't have any sanctions.

245
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:34,000
We were able to go to school, continue to go to school.

246
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:37,000
We were very much sought after.

247
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:43,000
We went to churches at night to see people greeted us with support.

248
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:49,000
They had dinners, you know, programs, they introduced us.

249
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:53,000
It was just like you guys did a wonderful thing.

250
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:58,000
And we really value and think, you know, that you're very special.

251
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Well, that's wonderful.

252
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:14,000
And we had lawyers that bailed us out of jail and would be with us in some of the meetings that we went to.

253
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:21,000
After that first sit in and you're arrested, did the sit-ins continue in Richmond or were things sort of on hold?

254
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:24,000
I can't remember.

255
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
I think I can't actually remember.

256
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,000
I know the next step was we were going to Mississippi.

257
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:33,000
We were going to have some buses and go into Mississippi.

258
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:38,000
I don't know how many students when I know that's my father put his foot down.

259
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:41,000
He says, no, you will not go.

260
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:45,000
You need to stay and you need to focus on getting your education.

261
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
I don't want you dead.

262
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:50,000
Did you fear it for my life?

263
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:52,000
And so, of course I listened.

264
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:54,000
Did you feel, did you want to go?

265
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:56,000
Oh, I was ready to go.

266
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:04,000
At that time, I think what it happened, if I had gone to Mississippi, I probably would have been either dead or still doing stuff.

267
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:08,000
And maybe, you know, I don't know, my life may have taken a different chair.

268
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:13,000
But it was, I stayed in school and I don't really remember Emily.

269
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:17,000
What happened, because at that time, we were busy.

270
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:23,000
We, all those of us who got arrested, because we had to go to court.

271
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,000
We had to meet with the lawyers.

272
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:28,000
We were going throughout the city.

273
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:34,000
So I don't even remember the other stuff that was going on.

274
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:43,000
I just remembered that when I got arrested, I had long fingernails and it had trouble fingerprinting me.

275
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:45,000
So I was arrested.

276
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:47,000
I was taken to jail.

277
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:49,000
And they were trying to fingerprint me.

278
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:51,000
And they had difficulty fingerprinting me.

279
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
And by the time they finished my lawyer was there to bail me out.

280
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:58,000
It was very tight.

281
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:02,000
I remember being very tired, you know, because it had been a long day.

282
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:06,000
And I remember that I had walked to the city, walked to the store.

283
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:09,000
We had walked and stood in line.

284
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:12,000
We had been pulled out, arrested.

285
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:16,000
We were, I just remember it was like dark after sex.

286
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:22,000
And I remember walking with my lawyer, who I don't remember, the name, anything now.

287
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:25,000
And a white man stood in front of me.

288
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:28,000
It was big and spit on me.

289
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
And said something and the lawyer just, you know, like, got it me out.

290
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:37,000
But at that time, I think I had lost all of my none ballad.

291
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:43,000
And I was ready to do battle, you know, because I guess I've always been a little militant.

292
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:45,000
And I was ready to take them on.

293
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,000
But I didn't.

294
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:50,000
We had to move on and we could not engage.

295
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:56,000
That was the thing that it was emphasized more than anything that we had to be peaceful.

296
00:29:56,000 --> 00:29:58,000
We had to be respectful.

297
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:00,000
And that went a long ways.

298
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:03,000
Did you worry that you might have trouble doing that?

299
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:04,000
No.

300
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:05,000
I didn't worry.

301
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:06,000
Only at that one point.

302
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:11,000
Because I think part of it was I was by myself at that time, because we had gotten separated.

303
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:16,000
I didn't know what had happened to my friends or anyone.

304
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:20,000
I don't even remember anyone being with me, but the lawyer whom I did know.

305
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:26,000
But there were a group of people who volunteered their time and their services to help us.

306
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:30,000
And so we didn't spend nights at something like an angel.

307
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:33,000
Like I said, I never saw a sale.

308
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:38,000
So did you feel good when you went and sat in that place that you've been excluded from?

309
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:39,000
I never went.

310
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:40,000
Oh, you did.

311
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:41,000
But I worked there.

312
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:42,000
Oh, yeah.

313
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:49,000
When I graduated from college and I taught another friend of mine, who we were teachers, you know.

314
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And we had student loans.

315
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
It was Christmas holidays and they were hiring people.

316
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,000
So we went down and we worked.

317
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:56,000
I remember I sold books.

318
00:30:56,000 --> 00:30:57,000
I worked in a book to book.

319
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:01,000
And I don't ever remember going to the Richmond rule.

320
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:02,000
Yeah.

321
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:03,000
I never remember that.

322
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:05,000
I've even excluded you didn't want to be a part of it.

323
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:06,000
I didn't want to be a part of it.

324
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:07,000
I never even crossed my mind.

325
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:10,000
You know, it was like the store was desegregated.

326
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:12,000
That's what we wanted, you know.

327
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:14,000
And that's what we had gotten.

328
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:17,000
So as long as you had access, you didn't really care what you went or not.

329
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:18,000
You didn't really care.

330
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:20,000
I didn't make any difference, you know.

331
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:27,000
But the people who wanted to, which was important, who wanted to do that, had the opportunity to do that.

332
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:31,000
Do you remember whether they integrated before the Civil Rights Act?

333
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:32,000
I don't remember.

334
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:33,000
Yeah.

335
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:43,000
You know, so a lot of this, you know, after I graduated, I taught at Maggie L. Walker (canonical first Black female bank president); the canonical Maggie L. Walker HS named for her High School, which was right down the street from Virginia Union.

336
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:48,000
I did my student teaching there in history.

337
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:53,000
And then from doing my student teaching, I actually got hired.

338
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:56,000
And so I came out of school and I taught.

339
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:00,000
And I taught for, I think, three years.

340
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:07,000
And I realized that I was so inexperienced from life, not so much the teaching I could do.

341
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:09,000
But the students were taller than I am.

342
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:12,000
They were more whirlies than I was.

343
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:16,000
And everything like that, that I decided I needed to have more.

344
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:19,000
Because remember, I couldn't go out when I was a child.

345
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:24,000
So I went to school, came home, or went to something function of baseball, a game with my brother.

346
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:27,000
So I didn't have the experience, knew nothing.

347
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:28,000
Okay.

348
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:32,000
And that's when I decided I would go, I needed, I wanted to get a master's.

349
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:39,000
I wanted to become a guidance counselor to be able to help students and to be better.

350
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:44,000
And that's when I went to the University of Maryland to get my master's.

351
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:49,000
And while there, I got a fellowship, so I ended up staying at one but two years.

352
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:53,000
And I never went back to Richmond after that.

353
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:57,000
So when you called your father after he saw it on TV?

354
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:00,000
I don't think he had seen it yet.

355
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:03,000
But he probably was a gentleman.

356
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:07,000
And he was, my dad was just, he was the best.

357
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:10,000
And you know, he said, I remember, are you okay?

358
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:11,000
Yeah.

359
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:13,000
I said, yeah, Dan, I'm okay.

360
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:15,000
He says, as long as you're okay, that's fine.

361
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:17,000
You need me, you call me.

362
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:19,000
I must have felt good.

363
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:20,000
I felt good, you know.

364
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:23,000
But that's the way he was all the time, you know.

365
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:24,000
Was your brother in Germany?

366
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:26,000
I mean, in the service by then?

367
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:27,000
He was in the service by then.

368
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:29,000
So he was not there.

369
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:33,000
He wasn't there to keep you off of the streets.

370
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Or either to get after me or say anything.

371
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:38,000
But, yeah.

372
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:40,000
You know, I know this happened at some schools,

373
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:43,000
but was there any protests or discussion ever

374
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:47,000
in your union about the restrictions on students at that time?

375
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:49,000
About signing out or anything like that?

376
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:50,000
We accepted it.

377
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:51,000
Yeah.

378
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:54,000
It was a small, black Baptist school.

379
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:59,000
So we had to go Sunday night, we had to go to BYPU or whatever that is.

380
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:02,000
You know, some kind of church services at night.

381
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,000
That was part of what we did, you know.

382
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:09,000
When we accepted that as a part of coming to school,

383
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:11,000
because those were the restrictions.

384
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:15,000
And if you didn't do it, it would affect your grades and things like that.

385
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:18,000
So to my knowledge, you know, we did our own way.

386
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:19,000
So we did our own way.

387
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:22,000
We did our own way.

388
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:25,000
We did it our own way.

389
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:27,000
There were ways of getting around stuff.

390
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:31,000
And I think we did, you know, without protesting everything.

391
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:32,000
You know, so.

392
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:33,000
Yeah.

393
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:36,000
One of the things I'm interested in, and I've been studying a little bit,

394
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:42,000
is with the sit-in movement, is the participation of men and women, you know.

395
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:46,000
And then, and I was wondering if you thought about that at all,

396
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:50,000
or if there were any discussions about, you know, whether it was safe for women.

397
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:51,000
No.

398
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:53,000
Or, you know, I should do this because no.

399
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:55,000
Don't remember any of that.

400
00:34:55,000 --> 00:35:00,000
It was just, you know, it was a group of students who decided that this was something they wanted to do.

401
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:01,000
Yeah.

402
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:02,000
They didn't, we didn't think about gender.

403
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:06,000
We didn't think about grade or age at that time.

404
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:11,000
I think I just, I was 18 when I went to school.

405
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:15,000
I think I'd just turned 19 in December and incidents with February.

406
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:21,000
So we were, we were some of us were young, some of us, you know, just didn't know the city.

407
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:25,000
But I mean, you know, if we almost, we didn't know the impact that we had,

408
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:27,000
or that we would have.

409
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:32,000
So that came as a big surprise, you know, to me it was, hey, we wanted to,

410
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:38,000
to say a great Richmond, we wanted to stop having to sit in the back of the bus.

411
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:43,000
We wanted to be able to eat, to go where we wanted to go, do what we wanted to do.

412
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:46,000
And that was all that was important, you know.

413
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:50,000
We wanted Patricia Washington to be able to go get her haircut anywhere she wanted to go, you know.

414
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:54,000
And so that was all we were thinking.

415
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:55,000
Yeah.

416
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:56,000
You know.

417
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:59,000
The, nothing else mattered.

418
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Yeah.

419
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:03,000
And did you have a pretty good idea before you were arrested?

420
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:06,000
Did you know the lawyers were going to support you and be there to get you out?

421
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Oh yeah.

422
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,000
So you didn't have to worry about like staying in jail.

423
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:14,000
Didn't worry about, didn't worry about all we had to do with our tasks was to go down,

424
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:19,000
was to pick it and to try to desegregate that room.

425
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:20,000
That was our task.

426
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:21,000
Yeah.

427
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:22,000
And that's all we focused on.

428
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:27,000
And we had to support, you know, financially, everything.

429
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:28,000
Yeah.

430
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:29,000
Yeah.

431
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:30,000
And I don't know if you would know.

432
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:33,000
So this happened in, you know, February of 1960.

433
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:34,000
Yeah.

434
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:41,000
And I know in April is when Miss Ella Baker called a meeting of student leaders from the sit-ins.

435
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:44,000
And that was at (Easter 1960) Shaw University.

436
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:47,000
And Charles Sherrod was one of the people who went to that.

437
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:49,000
Did you, were you aware of that at the time?

438
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:51,000
Or was that sort of just a kind of separate?

439
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:53,000
Sort of thing.

440
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:59,000
And then I think, so I would say that what happened at Virginia Union was just one incident.

441
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:00,000
Yeah.

442
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:01,000
Just one incident was focused on that.

443
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:04,000
As I remember, but that's like 50 years ago.

444
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:05,000
I know.

445
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:06,000
Okay.

446
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:08,000
So the death of my memory, that's all we did.

447
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:12,000
We focused on, that was our task, that was what we wanted to do.

448
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:20,000
Those of us who participated at that point, some people probably went on and continued to do sit-ins at other places and everything like that.

449
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:22,000
But my father, we focused to me.

450
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:26,000
So after that, first was like, okay, you did, but you had to do it.

451
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:27,000
You did it.

452
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:28,000
You wanted to do that.

453
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:29,000
You did that now.

454
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:33,000
You get back into the swing of things and get your education.

455
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:38,000
Did you ever consider pursuing the law degree or did you decide you had another interest?

456
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:39,000
A number of times.

457
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:40,000
A number of times.

458
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:41,000
A number of times.

459
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:47,000
I remember, I think I finally just realized that it would never be.

460
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:52,000
I remembered that at one point I thought about taking the L.S.A.T.

461
00:37:52,000 --> 00:38:01,000
This is an adult, as an adult, because once I got my, once I got my masters, I actually went to work for a private company.

462
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:04,000
And it was in Washington, D.C.

463
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:06,000
And it was an inner-city plant.

464
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:15,000
And my role was to try to get, it was black people trying to get them off the welfare roles, off drugs,

465
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:17,000
and out of jail.

466
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:22,000
So I was a counselor, and I had, whatever needed to be done, that's what I did.

467
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:29,000
So for years, I worked there, I want to say probably two years before moving to Minnesota.

468
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:33,000
So was this like the late 60s or the 70s?

469
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:35,000
The late 60s.

470
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:36,000
Yeah.

471
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:40,000
And did you enjoy that work?

472
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:41,000
I did.

473
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:42,000
Yeah.

474
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:43,000
I did.

475
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:50,000
I think part of, I always had to, I wanted, I always wanted to help people.

476
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:56,000
I wanted to see people survive and to do better.

477
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:07,000
So it was like, you know, getting someone out of jail, getting them on a path to learn and a trade was really a positive thing for me to do.

478
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:16,000
There were people who were single moms who lived in housing, and they couldn't get the landlock to fix a stove or something like that.

479
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:20,000
Part of, it was called an (federal) MA-4.

480
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:24,000
There were federal contracts that this company had.

481
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:32,000
And the goal, as I said, was to get people who were unemployable, employed, and to keep them employed.

482
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:46,000
So I worked there with that company for over 17 and a half years, but I moved from Washington to Minnesota, then back to Washington, and then to California, then to Minnesota.

483
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And that's where I was before I came to Massachusetts.

484
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:57,000
Did you see any connections between that work and the Civil Rights Movement?

485
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:15,000
When you think about it, I think the Civil Rights was about helping people, helping people to get their rights, to be able to vote, to be able to spend their money where they wanted to be,

486
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:24,000
helping people to become good citizens where they can become viable, take care of themselves, own homes.

487
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:26,000
Yeah, I did.

488
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:30,000
And that's how I've seen my life.

489
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:33,000
I've been a mentor.

490
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:37,000
We were talking about my husband who's a trustee at his school.

491
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:40,000
We shared a lot, but I didn't share this.

492
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:50,000
I went with him a couple of times, and I would say to the lady at the receptionist, we were in a store, like a TJ Maxx.

493
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:54,000
She says, oh, she says, that's in Rochester or Buffalo.

494
00:40:54,000 --> 00:41:01,000
I said, okay, and Rochester's like 60 miles, I took the keys, and I went to Rochester.

495
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:09,000
And I did it so like about three or four times, and then one time Fred would have things he had to do at night.

496
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:18,000
They'd be in meetings like from eight to five, they'd come home, five, thirty, they'd need to change your clothes, a bus was going to pick us up and take us to a reception or dinner right.

497
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:22,000
I slid in at six o'clock one night.

498
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:28,000
And Fred simply said to me, Jen, you're going to need to find something else to keep you losing.

499
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:31,000
And I said, okay, and I got the message.

500
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:36,000
So I sometimes I present training at the school.

501
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:41,000
I've done resume counseling with students, and I've also been a mentor.

502
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:44,000
And this is at Alfred University.

503
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:50,000
And I actually was appointed to the Leadership Advisory Board.

504
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:54,000
I was going to say you've got an award from them recently.

505
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:58,000
I was named in Honorary Alumni.

506
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:01,000
It was about two years ago, I think.

507
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:03,000
Two or three.

508
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:07,000
And did you, was part of that work with the Women's Center or something?

509
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:10,000
It was with the Women's Center.

510
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:17,000
So what happened was the Women's Center, Leadership Center, and then there was another part that was the Leadership Center.

511
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:23,000
One of the sponsors of the Women's Leadership Center died in a tragic accident.

512
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:34,000
And we renamed the Center, the Judson's Leadership Center, and they consolidated part of the Women's Program with the Leadership Program.

513
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:37,000
And I still am active with that.

514
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:43,000
In fact, we were talking, I have a meeting, a couple of weeks back there.

515
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:47,000
And that's where I, you know, I've been to the students.

516
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:51,000
And October, I'll be doing a training there as well.

517
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:54,000
Can you tell me what you enjoy about that?

518
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:57,000
Again, is that helping people in sharing.

519
00:42:57,000 --> 00:42:58,000
Yeah.

520
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:05,000
I really, you know, I'd like being able to give back, you know, because I feel that so many people gave to me.

521
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:11,000
When I was that young person in that city where the sailors and everybody,

522
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:23,000
there are people who helped me to move on and to move out and supported me to go on to do what I've done so far.

523
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:28,000
And so that's what I really enjoy giving back, you know.

524
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:34,000
You said earlier when we were talking, maybe even on tape, that you haven't talked about being part of this city.

525
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:36,000
Never talked about it.

526
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:51,000
The first time that it came up was two years ago, I think it was, when they had the 50th anniversary and somebody started calling me saying you have to come, you should come and all about that.

527
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:55,000
And I sort of said, yeah, okay.

528
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:59,000
And all in finally, I think Fred said, Jen, you should go.

529
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:04,000
And his job was so that he could not go at the time, but he said, you should go.

530
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:14,000
And my niece lives in Richmond and my oldest nephew, they came to see me and they were really impressed.

531
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:19,000
And when I went, I was, I didn't realize the effect that we had had.

532
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:21,000
We were given credit. I couldn't believe it.

533
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:24,000
Credit for desegregating Richmond, Virginia.

534
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:25,000
The city?

535
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:27,000
I didn't know that.

536
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:28,000
Yeah.

537
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:29,000
Didn't I know that?

538
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:33,000
And I go to campus and here's a plaque and there's my name.

539
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:40,000
You know, I'm saying, oh my God, this is just from what we did that many years ago.

540
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:42,000
Had no idea, Emily.

541
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:43,000
So no idea.

542
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:44,000
Different idea.

543
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:48,000
Different perspective, but I still haven't shared it with a lot of people.

544
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:52,000
And I don't know why, maybe because I don't want to know people know I'm so old.

545
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:55,000
They've been subpoenaing me.

546
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:57,000
Let me get you in on a secret.

547
00:44:57,000 --> 00:44:59,000
A lot of people can't do math.

548
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:01,000
That's good boy.

549
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:03,000
So you can tell them all.

550
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:04,000
I can tell them all.

551
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:07,000
You know, because I have a, like at one point, I was a child prodigy.

552
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:08,000
I was a child prodigy.

553
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:14,000
And at one point I thought about inviting some people to this and then I said, oh, I don't know.

554
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:16,000
I'm going to try to get through it myself.

555
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:21,000
And then I started thinking one time, well, what do I have to really say?

556
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:26,000
You know, I mean, we did it because we wanted to.

557
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:27,000
That's it.

558
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:32,000
Well, I know you said that you were interested in history, major dinner, and you're majoring in it.

559
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:36,000
Totted and continued to have an interest in it.

560
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:39,000
And, you know, I mean, I don't know.

561
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:40,000
Here you are.

562
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:42,000
You're somebody who's had an impact.

563
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:49,000
Everybody has some sort of impact on history, but yours is one that's a little bit more visible as part of the sit-in.

564
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:51,000
And my job doesn't know it.

565
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:53,000
Nobody at my work knows this.

566
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:58,000
So, do you think at all about sharing it or that it might be important?

567
00:45:58,000 --> 00:45:59,000
I don't know.

568
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:01,000
You know, I go, you go back to that age thing.

569
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:03,000
Well, it's you somebody, oh, you were back then.

570
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:04,000
You went back to the dinner, right?

571
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:05,000
Back in the day.

572
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:07,000
So, I don't know.

573
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:10,000
And then, I don't know why.

574
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:15,000
It's just, you know, like washing your face, cleaning your teeth.

575
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:17,000
This is something that I did.

576
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:19,000
I was very young.

577
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:21,000
It was something very important to me.

578
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:23,000
Very meaningful for me.

579
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:25,000
I have no regrets.

580
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:26,000
And doing it.

581
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:28,000
But I'm not a person who brags.

582
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:31,000
Or talk about any accomplishments or anything.

583
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:33,000
I really talk about the accomplishment of my husband.

584
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:34,000
Yeah.

585
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:36,000
Well, I think has, you know, done a great job.

586
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:39,000
And it's a very, very brilliant man that I enjoy.

587
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:44,000
And my son, those are the things that I, you know, share.

588
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:46,000
And have them have the love.

589
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:49,000
I guess a little bit of self-filling me.

590
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:51,000
You know, it's interesting to hear you say that.

591
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:53,000
Because of course, I, you know, I teach.

592
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:54,000
Yeah.

593
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:05,000
And, um, and for my students, one of the things that seems to be most meaningful them for them is to talk to people who did something when they were the same age.

594
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:06,000
Yeah, probably.

595
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:10,000
And they say, oh, wow, then it makes me think I can do something.

596
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:11,000
Yeah, probably.

597
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:14,000
You know, there's all these things going on in the world.

598
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:16,000
Sometimes they feel overwhelmed.

599
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:19,000
And so if you ever talk to the students at Alfred.

600
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:21,000
Maybe she or I think just to hear.

601
00:47:21,000 --> 00:47:24,000
I might, I think now.

602
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:28,000
And so there's so many other things that I'm involved in.

603
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:43,000
And with students, the Springfield chapter of LINKS Incorporated, we have, we have young girls that we work, Susan that we work with to try to be, you know, someone to consider she rolls.

604
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:49,000
To these young girls who maybe not have others that maybe sometimes I might share.

605
00:47:49,000 --> 00:48:07,000
And I might even share it with some of the members of my organization because what it tells us is that, you know, you can't have an impact, you know, and it's important to share your skills and your knowledge and everything that you've learned and acquired, you know.

606
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:09,000
Can you talk about that?

607
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:11,000
Well, it always is.

608
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:13,000
We're back.

609
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:17,000
Can you tell me a little bit about that organization and the work?

610
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:24,000
So this organization is called the LINKS Incorporated LINKS Incorporated. Incorporated.

611
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:29,000
It's a national women's organization made up predominantly of African American women.

612
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:38,000
It started in Philadelphia, about a hundred years ago, many years ago, because for social and friendship.

613
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:44,000
And now we have spread all out, we're international as well as national.

614
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And we have six facets that we operate under, you know, its health and wellness, the arts, national trends and services, international trends and services.

615
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:04,000
I think I left one out youth, services to youth.

616
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:12,000
And so what our program center around those facets, and this group that I'm in is out of Springfield.

617
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:18,000
So what we've done is we've assessed the community of Springfield, which has a lot of needs.

618
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:23,000
And we've started to try to mentor young girls.

619
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:31,000
And some of them are parents that have no parenting skills, don't know how to interface with the schools.

620
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:37,000
We've also started to support a house that is called a village.

621
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:43,000
It's women who have been incarcerated and on drugs.

622
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:53,000
And so what we're doing, the organization is made up of people, such as myself, an executive counselor, trained executive counselor, human resources.

623
00:49:53,000 --> 00:50:13,000
I know about jobs, searching and those things that we take our skills and we present workshops, counseling and tutoring and coaching these women to get successfully overcome their addictions, become better parents, get jobs, get their own homes.

624
00:50:13,000 --> 00:50:20,000
And so we meet in Springfield in that surrounding area, monthly.

625
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And we have projects that we work as well.

626
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:26,000
How far has Springfield from here?

627
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:30,000
About 50 miles, and the less than 50 miles.

628
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:34,000
And so are you seeing progress?

629
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,000
We've seen a lot of progress.

630
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:39,000
We've also supported some of the young girls who have...

631
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:43,000
So let me back up a number of the people in there, lawyers.

632
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:49,000
We have one young, one lady who's a very good friend of mine who's a superior court judge.

633
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:52,000
And we have a writer, we have different people.

634
00:50:52,000 --> 00:51:02,000
And we've actually stuck with some of these young ladies and seen them graduate from high school, go on to college.

635
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:04,000
We keep in touch with some of them.

636
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:12,000
We also have an English, a blue sheet teaches English, a UMass Amherst, linguist, linguistics.

637
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:20,000
And she's actually sort of mentoring a young lady who graduated from high school and has gone on to UMass.

638
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:24,000
So she's there with her and sort of, you know, continuing to work with her.

639
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:28,000
So with Springfield, we've done some things in the city.

640
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:32,000
We've seen as much, it's just a lot of work that needs to be done there.

641
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
That must be rewarding.

642
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:35,000
It is, it is.

643
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:38,000
Is it hard to keep up with that and your work?

644
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:42,000
Well, you know, I actually, I've been involved in a lot of things.

645
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:48,000
And I began to scale back a little bit because so I lived here in Northborough, Massachusetts.

646
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:52,000
And I actually was a library trustee for a couple of years.

647
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:55,000
I was chaired to Community Affairs Committee,

648
00:51:55,000 --> 00:52:03,000
which did things in the community to enhance the life of the citizens and everything like we did.

649
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:05,000
We do town clean-up.

650
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:09,000
We've done some of concerts in the park that tree, everything like that side chair.

651
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:11,000
That's like 15 years.

652
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:16,000
And I chair the personnel board for the town.

653
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:22,000
Well, two years ago, my husband decided that I should do something different.

654
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:23,000
And I said, okay.

655
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:28,000
And he says, there's a vacancy for the Assabet Valley Regional School District.

656
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:29,000
You should run.

657
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:30,000
I said, I'm not running Fred.

658
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:32,000
He said, oh, yeah, you should run.

659
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:33,000
It'd be something nice to do.

660
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:34,000
I said, I'm not running.

661
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:35,000
I got enough to do.

662
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:38,000
So he says, well, nobody signed up.

663
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:40,000
The date went by and everything like that.

664
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:42,000
So he says, well, you should do it right in.

665
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:43,000
You're Fred.

666
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:45,000
So Fred told a few people.

667
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:48,000
And I won, do it right in.

668
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:55,000
So now I'm a school committee member for regional school, vocational technical school.

669
00:52:55,000 --> 00:52:58,000
And sometimes I wonder why.

670
00:52:58,000 --> 00:53:01,000
So I did start in a writing.

671
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:03,000
I know he does.

672
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:04,000
He has a campaign.

673
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:07,000
So I have to get signatures when he's running.

674
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:09,000
So you have to have like 50 signatures.

675
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:15,000
So, but he likes to do more than 50 because suppose somebody isn't a registered voter or something like that.

676
00:53:16,000 --> 00:53:19,000
So I help him to get signatures because he runs every year.

677
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:23,000
But so I did step down as a library trustee.

678
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And I step down as the chair of the Community Affairs Committee.

679
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:31,000
So I still chair the personal board and the S.V.V. Valley.

680
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And then I do my work with Alfred University.

681
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:36,000
And so I do a lot of mentoring.

682
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:39,000
I do a lot of miniature, an HR manager.

683
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:44,000
And I stay very busy with my job.

684
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:51,000
I used to, in addition to being a HR manager to hear the alternative dispute resolution,

685
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:58,000
which is an or was a process where if a person felt they were not being treated fairly or something like that,

686
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:07,000
they could come and present their case, be evaluated, and either have a reversal or it would remain the same.

687
00:54:07,000 --> 00:54:10,000
So was that within the company or is that within the company?

688
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:15,000
Did that work well to avoid conflict or failure?

689
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:21,000
It does. It's very similar to, so if you're in a union, you have the five steps.

690
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:23,000
But it's a professional you don't.

691
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:25,000
So this is a way of working.

692
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:28,000
And it helps both the employee and the company.

693
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:29,000
But then it doesn't stop.

694
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:36,000
Sometimes people continue on to do lawsuits or MCAD, discrimination suits and everything like that.

695
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:40,000
So everything has sort of been along the same lines.

696
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:45,000
Mentoring, coaching, helping throughout my career.

697
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:48,000
And you mentioned your husband and his elections and his work.

698
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:51,000
So could you say just a little bit about that?

699
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:54,000
So there's some context for the, for other people.

700
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:58,000
Well, when I met my husband, he was a selectman.

701
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:06,000
And a selectman is in the state in Massachusetts, is like a city council.

702
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:09,000
And so he was a member of the city council.

703
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:14,000
And instead of having a chair, a mayor, you would, one of the members would chair.

704
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:16,000
So he's been a selectman.

705
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:18,000
He's chaired the board of selectman.

706
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:22,000
But prior to that, he was actually chair of the personal board.

707
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:25,000
And then he became, like I said, a selectman.

708
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:30,000
And then he's been a town moderator for 10 years.

709
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:37,000
The town moderator is, we have the old style government where you have town meetings.

710
00:55:37,000 --> 00:55:45,000
And anybody who's a registered voter can come, be heard, listen to the budget, you know, questions and everything like that.

711
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:53,000
And his job is to facilitate that meeting and to keep it orderly, to get the budget passed or whatever needs to happen.

712
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,000
And it is all of any conflicts.

713
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:58,000
And all like that.

714
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:03,000
And plus, there's favorite thing I think is he appoints members to certain boards.

715
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:05,000
And so he's my boss.

716
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:08,000
He reminds me quite frequently. He's my boss.

717
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:12,000
So as a, as a personal board member, he appoints me.

718
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:22,000
But I was floored, Emily, when I had learned that he called the town administrator to see how, how had I done my job?

719
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:25,000
I can't believe it.

720
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:28,000
So how do you separate the work in coming home?

721
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:31,000
Very well.

722
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:39,000
I think we both, we both like and enjoy community work.

723
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:45,000
And like I was saying on a way coming over here, he was being very supportive and coming with me today.

724
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:52,000
But the third weekend of September, he will be so busy because he's the Applefest celebration.

725
00:56:52,000 --> 00:57:00,000
And we have an Applefest celebration every year about the third weekend in September.

726
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:05,000
So we'll have a parade, we'll have fireworks, we'll have concerts and everything.

727
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:08,000
And he does all the announcing.

728
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:11,000
So are you keep busy?

729
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:16,000
So we both keep busy in town and we try to be supportive of each other.

730
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:23,000
And I can speak for him. I don't know, I let him speak for me, but I think it's extremely supportive for me.

731
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:26,000
I couldn't do it without him because it's nice.

732
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:29,000
He's also a human resources.

733
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:33,000
He has his own consulting practice.

734
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:40,000
And so he works with small and medium sized companies sort of consulting, human capital consulting and things like that.

735
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:45,000
And so we have the ability to share our work.

736
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:55,000
And sometimes if I want to just bounce something off of him, that I can, because I know I'll get a fair assessment and honest assessment.

737
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:01,000
Have you thought about running to be town moderator, so that you could be his boss?

738
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:04,000
Oh, no point in to afford him.

739
00:58:04,000 --> 00:58:08,000
You have to know, you have to know Robert's Rules of Order.

740
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:10,000
You have to be patient.

741
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:13,000
And you have to speak very well.

742
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:20,000
And he has a very, I mean, sometimes we go on sometimes and somebody said, oh, you should be on radio.

743
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:22,000
You should be an announcer.

744
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:24,000
I'd just say.

745
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:26,000
But he's done that, been there.

746
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:30,000
And sometimes I think he thinks he should do voiceover or something.

747
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:34,000
But I don't have the patience, the knowledge or the ability.

748
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:37,000
I would probably, he stays what I admire.

749
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:45,000
Not a lot of things about him, but he doesn't show any favoritism or anything on his face.

750
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:49,000
I probably would be saying, you need to sit down and shut up.

751
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:52,000
That's sort of like when the lawyer walking back out.

752
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:55,000
You're exactly, exactly.

753
00:58:55,000 --> 00:58:58,000
And you're riddled of five days, right?

754
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:04,000
You know, that's, I mean, one of the things I'm also interested in.

755
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:07,000
I was going to say one of the things I'm also interested in with the Civil Rights Room

756
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:10,000
and is non-violence and how it works.

757
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:13,000
And I think a lot of people have an image of the Civil Rights Room

758
00:59:13,000 --> 00:59:17,000
and as just being completely non-violent and nobody ever had any urge for anything else.

759
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:18,000
No, no, no.

760
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:19,000
So a lot about anything else.

761
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:20,000
That's not true.

762
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:29,000
I mean, if you get spit, spit on, it's hard not to be angry or not to show some emotions.

763
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:34,000
Did you encounter any of that when you were marching to downtown that day?

764
00:59:34,000 --> 00:59:38,000
Just the, people were yelling at us calling us names and everything.

765
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:45,000
And you just sort of had to just keep focused on your goal and don't make eye contact.

766
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:47,000
That's how we had to do it.

767
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:54,000
And so as we look at them, you actually give in to them and you're acknowledging them.

768
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:58,000
So you just keep, for you go on, don't look, don't respond or anything.

769
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:01,000
And did it help that you were doing that with your close friends?

770
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:03,000
Well, we got separated.

771
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:05,000
We were separated, right away.

772
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:07,000
I don't, I don't even remember.

773
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:09,000
I think I got arrested before them.

774
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:10,000
Yeah.

775
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:13,000
And, or, I'm not sure.

776
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:14,000
Yeah.

777
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:21,000
So when you went back to Richmond for this reunion and Virginia Union and found out that, you know,

778
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:24,000
people were saying you had this huge impact and stuff.

779
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:28,000
And what was it like to be back together with the students who had done that?

780
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:32,000
I wonder if I had not seen Marie (Sallasin) and Pat and Patricia Washington in years.

781
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:41,000
So the first thing, you know, we had an opportunity to catch up because Marie (Sallasin) and Pat had married a person who was in a military

782
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:48,000
and she had traveled all over and we'd lost contact with each other.

783
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:53,000
And Patricia Washington still lives in Philadelphia, outside of Philadelphia.

784
01:00:53,000 --> 01:00:58,000
A newer husband had met them when they were dating so it was good to catch up.

785
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:04,000
Overwhelming to see what really people were saying.

786
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:06,000
They were calling us heroes.

787
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:13,000
So, okay, this (group of) 34, 34, desegregated the city of Richmond.

788
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:14,000
Yeah.

789
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:15,000
Did you know we did that?

790
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:16,000
Yeah.

791
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:17,000
Wow, that's wonderful.

792
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:18,000
Yeah.

793
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:26,000
To know, and I guess I was very proud that I had made the decision to participate and this was the result.

794
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:30,000
Do you think about the status of civil rights today?

795
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:31,000
I do.

796
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:32,000
I do.

797
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
Do you have any thoughts that you'd like to share on that?

798
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:35,000
You know, always have thoughts.

799
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:47,000
The first thought that I have, and this will come as a surprise to that I believe that racism is still rampant and apparent in the United States today.

800
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:55,000
I believe, I was well, I will say, I was so shocked when Obama was elected president.

801
01:01:55,000 --> 01:02:03,000
I did not think that I would live to see an African-American president never in my Wallace dreams.

802
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:06,000
I thought that was something my son would experience.

803
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:16,000
However, although he was elected, I think it's racism that has been a part of the issues that he [Obama] has faced.

804
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:26,000
I mean, and that people would just get me so upset is that intelligent people don't see this and don't put a stop to it.

805
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:32,000
You know, there are so many senators and representatives that should never go back to Congress.

806
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:38,000
I mean, they sit and have lunch and say, hey, we're not going to agree or accept anything that he does.

807
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:39,000
How could you do that?

808
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:45,000
How could you not give this brilliant man an opportunity to be successful?

809
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:47,000
Racism is still alive.

810
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:57,000
And there are other things, but that's the one that just, you know, and there's something, and I think sometimes, you know, what can I do?

811
01:02:57,000 --> 01:02:58,000
What should I do?

812
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:10,000
And like I said, to Fred sometimes, I think I should just quit and go work for, you know, try to work for Obama, do something to try, because it's not over.

813
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:13,000
We still have a lot to do.

814
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:19,000
But the good news is that our children don't see color today, you know.

815
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:32,000
And I have this conversation with my sister, who lives outside of Washington and the police call Looksville, and they're menaces, and where they chose to live, just as we're Fred and I have chosen to live.

816
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,000
There are very few African Americans.

817
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:37,000
So my sons, friends, are all white.

818
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:39,000
Does that mean?

819
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:48,000
And his cousins are the people of color that he knows closely and cares about and relates to.

820
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:54,000
But when we talked about having four and five kids at our house, the wrong way.

821
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:58,000
Does that create different kinds of challenges?

822
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:02,000
I don't think so. I think for them, it's easier.

823
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:08,000
You know, my son has never known about having to sit in the back of the bus.

824
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:16,000
My son doesn't, I think, well, I think he, in my opinion, and of course my husband may have a different opinion.

825
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:22,000
When he was in the seventh grade, I think it was, he came home and announced he wanted his hair braided.

826
01:04:22,000 --> 01:04:24,000
I said, okay.

827
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:27,000
So we can't have routine every Sunday night.

828
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:30,000
We said that if something, he'd take his hair out and I'd braid it.

829
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:36,000
I think it was about the only African American in his class, and that was his way of showing that he was different.

830
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:41,000
And he wore his hair braided until he got to high school.

831
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:44,000
And now he wears a fume.

832
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:51,000
The only thing, the only time he could, the summertime, he'll cut it because it's hot.

833
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:54,000
But my man lets his hair, he used to play in a band too.

834
01:04:54,000 --> 01:05:01,000
And he's like, I don't know if he's a big hair girl, it looks something like Lionel Richie.

835
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:09,000
This is the jazz, I don't have (Lionel) Lionel Richie.

836
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:14,000
But he looks like a, a Molly, Bob Marley, how Bob had the big hair.

837
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:19,000
My son has the big hair, you know, so he doesn't hide his ethnicity.

838
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:22,000
He cuts it, you can't tell.

839
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:27,000
Sometimes I have friends in California who say if he's coming out there, please have him shave and everything

840
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:34,000
because he may take him part of a Muslim or some Islam that goes shot or whatever.

841
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:38,000
Does he see the existence of racism still?

842
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:40,000
I don't think so.

843
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:45,000
No, he never sees things in terms of color, which is good.

844
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:52,000
So, I mean if something happens to, in our day, if something happened to you, you didn't get promoted

845
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:56,000
or you didn't do something, it was because of your race, he doesn't see that.

846
01:05:56,000 --> 01:05:59,000
You may see partiality.

847
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:02,000
But he doesn't see race.

848
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:09,000
Well, can you think of things that are important, things that you think people should think about or know about?

849
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:12,000
Things I haven't thought to ask you.

850
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:22,000
Oh, I'm thinking.

851
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:32,000
I don't know.

852
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:34,000
That's a big question.

853
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:37,000
I'm just trying to think about it.

854
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:48,000
I guess for me, just thinking about me, I think that I've always had the civil rights fight in my blood.

855
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:54,000
On my job and my life, I will fight for what I think is right.

856
01:06:54,000 --> 01:07:03,000
If something is happening a lot of times in my work, people come to me and they ask me for help.

857
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:06,000
And I will give them that help.

858
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:14,000
And it's off the record kind of thing, but it's more or less like, you know, they're dealing with, and I see racism.

859
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:16,000
I see it, you know.

860
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:26,000
And I've been trying to figure out how do you get others to see the racism that exists because it's so subtle.

861
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:40,000
For example, if you hire, you can hire a person of color or a female, but you may not give them the total job or the job that they can be most successful in.

862
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:47,000
And, or you can finally maybe hire a person of color who's very, very good and you won't let them move.

863
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:51,000
They keep them right in that position because you don't want to lose them.

864
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:54,000
But you lose them anyway because they go to another company.

865
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:59,000
So what I've been trying to, I'll just give you some.

866
01:07:59,000 --> 01:08:05,000
Lately, our company seems to be changing the way they do business.

867
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:07,000
We'll have the old type HR.

868
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:09,000
So they have business partners.

869
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:16,000
And so you're made, you end up with a lot of different projects, you know, salary planning, HR review, things like that.

870
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:19,000
But they don't look back at the basics.

871
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:32,000
And I had, I just, I had a couple of experiences that someone came to me that someone was complaining that someone went in the ladies room and a person said,

872
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:35,000
I think you have the wrong bathroom.

873
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:38,000
And so nobody thought anything of it, right?

874
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:48,000
And then I had somebody else to say, you know, there's someone visiting and we think that person is going through a chain.

875
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:57,000
So I'm working on transgender issues at my company and I'm this close to getting gender neutral bathroom,

876
01:08:57,000 --> 01:09:04,000
at least two general neutral bathrooms near the manufacturing floor because I work for a manufacturing company.

877
01:09:04,000 --> 01:09:08,000
There's like over 4,000 people, lots of square footage.

878
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:15,000
But there is no gender neutral bathroom so that if I'm transitioning, I have some place I can comfortably go.

879
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:19,000
Or if I'm just sick and I want to go someplace like that.

880
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:26,000
So I started that and then I had a situation where someone came to me and needed help.

881
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:42,000
And my role, that's my role, and trying to understand and trying to help that person that I'm actually helping to rewrite or put together training that talk to management and leaders about sensitive issues like this.

882
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:49,000
We've had it before, but in one situation, I mean an employee says to someone, when did you know your realizement?

883
01:09:49,000 --> 01:09:58,000
Or when did you know you were out with your back surgery instead of, you know, you out back surgery, did you transition?

884
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:01,000
It's like the inappropriate conversations and questions.

885
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:12,000
So I'm working with some people to try to train people to make things better because it's still, we got a long way to go.

886
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:20,000
So do you find resistance to that or is it just more like just kind of lethargy or no?

887
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:22,000
I think people just don't know.

888
01:10:22,000 --> 01:10:26,000
Some people just don't know and they just don't understand.

889
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:32,000
But then there are some people who are going through things and they don't know how to deal.

890
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:42,000
The recent situation I had is where a person, it was one of the female, but feels that he is a male.

891
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:44,000
But he's taken no steps.

892
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:54,000
So people don't understand and he, I think, hasn't really gotten his mind wrapped around that.

893
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:58,000
And so people, he feels people discriminate on harass him.

894
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:04,000
But harassing, saying, did you have a sex change, isn't really harassing. That's an appropriate.

895
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:09,000
So training people, not to ask personal and appropriate questions.

896
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:15,000
So I mean, so yeah. So it goes from one thing to another.

897
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:19,000
But it's all related. It's all related.

898
01:11:19,000 --> 01:11:33,000
And it's about understanding differences, valuing the differences, and letting people have their own ability to make their choices and to live their choices.

899
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:39,000
So I'm trying to think now, what's my next step?

900
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:46,000
You know, am I going to teach? Am I just going to sit home and read like one of my girlfriends?

901
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:48,000
Or I don't see that.

902
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:53,000
I see so many shaking hands behind you.

903
01:11:53,000 --> 01:12:01,000
But I'm thinking about transitioning myself to figure out maybe more community work and not sure.

904
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:06,000
So you think you might want different challenges coming up in the future.

905
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:11,000
I'm really proud of myself if I get those two bathrooms at that company.

906
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:14,000
I had some waiting, you know, it's budget. I got support.

907
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:16,000
It's now getting the budget to do that.

908
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:20,000
So you've been able to convince people it's a good thing. It's just a question of actually now implementing.

909
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:21,000
Right.

910
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:27,000
Right. And then next step is completing a training where I'll help the trained managers.

911
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:32,000
What do you do? How do you do? And, you know, just coach.

912
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:36,000
Yeah. So it sounds like some major accomplishments for me.

913
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:38,000
Yeah. Yeah.

914
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:43,000
So can you think of any final thoughts or we can take a second and think about it too?

915
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:50,000
No. I think I just about, I'm shared just about everything that I can.

916
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:52,000
Well, we really appreciate it.

917
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:57,000
And we're very pleased to have your story as part of the Civil Rights History Project.

918
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:00,000
I hope it's helpful. It is. Thank you.

919
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:02,000
Thank you. Thank you.

920
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:11,000
It has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

